(1)

Create a map of the 48 states in the continental United States with ggplot2. Make sure the state names are displayed in title-case on the map, along with the state borders. Title the map with an appropriate title. Make sure the legend is not visible.

library(ggplot2)
library(ggmap)
library(maps)
library(maptools)
library(ggthemes)
library(ggrepel)

state.df <- map_data("state")

library(stringr)
state.df$state = str_to_title(state.df$region)

library(sp)
getLabelPoint <- function(state) {
    Polygon(state[c("long", "lat")])@labpt
}
centroids = by(state.df, state.df$state, 
    getLabelPoint)  # Returns list
centroids2 <- do.call("rbind.data.frame", 
    centroids)  # Convert to Data Frame
centroids2$statename = rownames(centroids)
names(centroids2) <- c("clong", "clat", "statename")

ggplot(state.df, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group)) + 
    geom_polygon(aes(fill = region), color = "white") + 
    coord_fixed(1.3) + geom_text_repel(data = centroids2, 
    aes(x = clong, y = clat, group = statename, 
        label = statename), size = 3.5) + 
    theme_map() + theme(legend.position = "none") + 
    labs(title = "Map of the 48 States in the Continental United States")

(2)

Now create a data-frame of Californiaâs counties. Use this link to download CA countiesâ 2018 Health Ranking data. The measure you want is the % Obese so read-in this measure (along with county names) as a data-frame. Now you need to create a map of CA counties, with the county names displayed, and the map filled-in with the quartiles of obesity (Hint: You want the FOUR groups to be labeled â0-25â, â25-50â, â50-75â, â75-100â). Title the map and make sure the legend is visible, along with a caption that provides the source of the obesity measure. Place the legend at the bottom of the map.

Now, does it look like counties in CA have a spatial pattern to obesity (i.e., are the counties in the 75-100 group â the ones with the highest obesity levels â clustered together or does the map exhibit no pattern)?

cacounties <- map_data("county", region = "CA")

cacounties$county = str_to_title(cacounties$subregion)

getLabelPoint <- function(county) {
    Polygon(county[c("long", "lat")])@labpt
}
centroids = by(cacounties, cacounties$county, 
    getLabelPoint)  # Returns list
centroids2 <- do.call("rbind.data.frame", 
    centroids)  # Convert to Data Frame
centroids2$countyname = rownames(centroids)
names(centroids2) <- c("clong", "clat", "countyname")

library(readxl)
obesity <- read_excel("~/Documents/Teaching/mpa5830/data/cacountiesCHR.xlsx")

my.df = merge(cacounties, obesity, by = "county", 
    all.x = TRUE, sort = FALSE)

my.df = my.df[order(my.df$order), ]

library(dplyr)
my.df2 <- my.df %>% mutate(grouped_obesity = cut(obesity, 
    breaks = c(quantile(my.df$obesity, probs = seq(0, 
        1, by = 0.25))), labels = c("0-25", 
        "25-50", "50-75", "75-100"), include.lowest = TRUE))

ggplot(my.df2, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group)) + 
    geom_polygon(aes(fill = grouped_obesity), 
        color = "white") + coord_fixed(1.3) + 
    geom_text_repel(data = centroids2, aes(x = clong, 
        y = clat, group = countyname, label = countyname), 
        size = 3.5, color = "black", fontface = "bold") + 
    scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel2", 
        direction = -1) + theme_map() + theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
    labs(title = "Obesity in California Counties", 
        fill = "Quartiles of % Population Obese", 
        caption = "Source: County Health Rankings (2018)")

The map does show a spatial pattern, with many of the counties in a particular obesity quartile tending to be adjacent to one another. The only ones that are not, for the highest obesity levels, are Imperial and Humboldt.

(3)

Use Google maps to find the latitude/longitude of THREE hospitals closest to your current place of residence. Note the name of each hospital as well. Now use leaflet to generate a map that shows each of these three hospitals as popups. Display the hospitalsâ names.

library(leaflet)
library(leaflet.extras)
library(widgetframe)

hospitals <- data.frame(names = c("Ohio Health O'Bleness Hospital", 
    "Ohio University Student Health Center", 
    "Athens Medical Associates"), nlat = c(39.334411, 
    39.331622, 39.35153), nlng = c(-82.123221, 
    -82.097986, -82.095325))

pl1 <- leaflet() %>% setView(lat = 39.332577, 
    lng = -82.106336, zoom = 13) %>% addMarkers(lat = hospitals$nlat, 
    lng = hospitals$nlng, popup = hospitals$names) %>% 
    addProviderTiles(providers$Esri.NatGeoWorldMap) %>% 
    setMapWidgetStyle() %>% frameWidget(height = "475")
pl1

(4)

Using the epa data-set create four graphics â a bar-chart, a scatter-plot, a histogram, and a box-plot. Display all four graphics on a single canvas via patchwork. Make sure you label the graphsâ components (at minimum, the axis-labels and a title).

library(ggplot2)
library(hrbrthemes)
library(patchwork)

load("~/Documents/Teaching/mpa5830/data/epa.RData")

p1 <- ggplot(epa, aes(x = fuelType1, fill = fuelType1)) + 
    geom_bar() + labs(x = "Fuel Type", y = "Frequency", 
    title = "Bar-chart of Fuel Types") + 
    coord_flip() + theme_ipsum_rc() + theme(title = element_text(size = 7), 
    legend.position = "none")
p2 <- ggplot(epa, aes(x = city08, y = highway08)) + 
    geom_point(color = "cornflowerblue") + 
    labs(x = "City miles per gallon", y = "Highway miles per gallon", 
        title = "Scatterplot: City & Highway mpg") + 
    theme(title = element_text(size = 7)) + 
    theme_ipsum_rc()
p3 <- ggplot(epa, aes(x = fuelCost08)) + 
    geom_histogram(bins = 10, fill = "coral", 
        color = "black") + labs(x = "Fuel Costs", 
    y = "Frequency", title = "Histogram of Fuel Costs") + 
    theme_ipsum_rc() + theme(title = element_text(size = 7))
p4 <- ggplot(subset(epa, ghgScore > 0), aes(x = 1, 
    y = ghgScore)) + geom_boxplot(fill = "magenta") + 
    coord_flip() + labs(y = "Greenhouse Gas Emissions' Score", 
    x = "", title = "Box-plot of GHG Emissions' Score") + 
    theme(title = element_text(size = 7)) + 
    theme_ipsum_rc()

p1 + p2 + p3 + p4 + plot_layout(ncol = 2)
